      fullDef: 'Real estate depreciation allows rental property owners to deduct a portion of the property\'s cost (excluding land) each year over its IRS-defined useful life: 27.5 years for residential rental property and 39 years for commercial. A $275,000 residential building generates $10,000 per year in depreciation deductions ($275,000 / 27.5).\n\nDepreciation is a "phantom" deduction—no cash leaves your pocket, but it reduces taxable income. A property generating $20,000 in taxable cash flow with $10,000 in depreciation results in only $10,000 of taxable income. High-income investors can use bonus depreciation and cost segregation studies to accelerate deductions.\n\nThe tax deferral is not permanent. When the property is sold, the IRS recaptures depreciation deductions taken at up to 25% (depreciation recapture tax). A 1031 exchange can defer this recapture indefinitely.',
