      fullDef: 'A proforma is a forward-looking financial model projecting income, expenses, NOI, cash flow, and returns under specified assumptions. Unlike historical financials (which show what actually happened), a proforma shows what the investor expects to happen—making the quality of its assumptions critical.\n\nA well-built proforma includes: gross potential rent, vacancy and credit loss, effective gross income, itemized operating expenses, NOI, debt service, and resulting cash flow. Multi-year proformas show how these figures evolve with assumed rent growth and expense inflation.\n\nBe skeptical of proformas provided by sellers—they often feature optimistic rents, minimal expenses, and zero vacancy. Always build your own proforma from verified actuals, independently confirmed market rents, and conservatively high expense assumptions.',
      example: 'The investor built a 10-year proforma projecting NOI growing from $62,000 to $87,000 at 3% annual rent growth, supporting an estimated exit value of $1.16 million at a 7.5% cap rate.',
      related: ['noi', 'cap-rate', 'cash-on-cash-return', 'due-diligence'],
