      term: 'Comorbidity',
      slug: 'comorbidity',
      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'The presence of two or more chronic medical conditions in the same patient at the same time, which often complicates treatment decisions.',
      fullDef: 'Comorbidity refers to the simultaneous presence of one or more additional health conditions in a patient alongside a primary condition. For example, a patient with type 2 diabetes often has comorbid hypertension, obesity, and dyslipidemia. Each condition independently increases disease burden and together they interact in ways that complicate management.\n\nComorbidities matter because they affect treatment choices (some medications safe in healthy patients are contraindicated in renal disease), prognosis (patients with multiple comorbidities have worse outcomes for any given condition), and healthcare utilization (comorbid patients have more hospitalizations and longer lengths of stay). Clinical trials often exclude patients with multiple comorbidities, making it harder to apply evidence directly to complex real-world patients.\n\nFor patients, disclosing all active conditions and all medications to every provider—including specialists who see you for one condition—is essential. Drug interactions, contraindications, and treatment conflicts across comorbid conditions are a leading cause of preventable medical errors.',
