      slug: 'symptom-tracker',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'A log—paper or digital—recording symptom occurrence, severity, triggers, and relieving factors to improve clinical communication and pattern recognition.',
      fullDef: 'A symptom tracker is any systematic method of recording health symptoms over time—when they occur, how severe they are (often on a 1–10 scale), associated factors, triggers, and what helps or worsens them. Paper diaries, smartphone apps, and wearable devices all serve this purpose. For conditions with intermittent or variable symptoms (migraines, IBS, seizures, mood disorders, joint pain), tracking over days to weeks reveals patterns invisible in a single clinic visit.\n\nSymptom trackers dramatically improve clinical consultations. Instead of a patient saying "I get headaches sometimes," a two-week headache diary showing headaches every third day, worse with dehydration, lasting 4–6 hours, and responding to ibuprofen gives the clinician actionable data to guide diagnosis and treatment. For chronic conditions, trackers enable objective assessment of treatment response over time.\n\nMany disease-specific apps exist for conditions like migraines, diabetes, asthma, and IBD. General health apps (Apple Health, MyFitnessPal, Bearable) allow broader symptom and lifestyle tracking. Even a simple notebook dated entry is better than trying to reconstruct several months of symptoms from memory at a medical appointment.',
