      letter: 'A',
      shortDef: 'A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction requiring immediate epinephrine treatment, characterized by hives, airway swelling, and circulatory collapse.',
      fullDef: 'Anaphylaxis is a rapid-onset, severe allergic reaction that is potentially fatal if not treated immediately. It involves the release of large amounts of histamine and other mediators from mast cells and basophils, causing: urticaria (hives) and angioedema (swelling), bronchospasm (wheezing, difficulty breathing), hypotension (low blood pressure), and circulatory collapse. Common triggers include foods (peanuts, tree nuts, shellfish, milk), medications (penicillin, NSAIDs), insect stings, and latex.\n\nEpinephrine (adrenaline) by auto-injector (EpiPen) is the only first-line treatment for anaphylaxis. It must be given immediately—antihistamines and corticosteroids are adjuncts, not substitutes. After epinephrine, the patient must go to an emergency department because biphasic reactions (a second wave of symptoms hours later) occur in up to 20% of cases.\n\nPatients with known anaphylaxis triggers should carry two epinephrine auto-injectors at all times, wear a medical ID bracelet, have a written anaphylaxis action plan, and avoid confirmed triggers. Allergen immunotherapy can desensitize some patients to specific triggers over time.',
      example: 'Within minutes of eating a dish containing hidden peanut oil, the teenager developed throat tightness and hives; her mother administered the EpiPen and called 911, and she recovered without intubation.',
