      fullDef: 'Credit card rewards programs return a percentage of spending to cardholders in the form of cash back (1–5% of purchase value returned as statement credit), travel miles (airline miles or flexible points redeemable for travel), or general-purpose points (redeemable for travel, merchandise, or cash back). Premium travel cards offer sign-up bonuses (often worth $500–$1,000 in travel after meeting a minimum spend requirement) and ongoing category bonuses (3–5x points on dining, travel, groceries).\n\nRewards are only valuable if you pay your balance in full monthly. The interest on a carried balance—at 20%+—vastly outpaces any rewards earned (1–5%). No rewards program is designed to be used while carrying a balance; the economics only work for those who never pay interest.\n\nFor maximizers, a strategy of 2–3 complementary cards covering different category bonuses can earn 3–8% effective return on spending. Annual fee cards (typically $95–$695) are worthwhile if their benefits (travel credits, lounge access, purchase protections) exceed the fee—do the math at renewal.',
