      term: 'Secured Credit Card',
      slug: 'secured-credit-card',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'A credit card backed by a cash deposit that serves as collateral, designed for people building or rebuilding credit with limited credit history.',
      fullDef: 'A secured credit card requires the cardholder to make a cash deposit—typically $200–$500—which becomes the credit limit and serves as collateral if the cardholder defaults. The card functions identically to a regular credit card for purchases, and payment history is reported to all three credit bureaus, making it an effective tool for building credit from scratch or repairing damaged credit.\n\nAfter 12–18 months of responsible use (paying on time, keeping utilization below 30%), most secured card issuers will upgrade the account to an unsecured card and return the deposit. Some issuers (Discover, Capital One) offer secured cards with the explicit pathway to graduation reviewed at 6–8 months. The deposit earns little or no interest, so the "cost" is the opportunity cost of that money being tied up.\n\nThe primary alternative for credit-building is a credit-builder loan from a credit union or Community Development Financial Institution (CDFI). Both tools work; a secured card is more widely available. The key is consistent on-time payment and low utilization—the behaviors that build the score, not the type of card.',
      example: 'After a bankruptcy discharge, the consumer opened a $300 secured card, charged only $60/month (20% utilization), and paid it in full each month; after 18 months her FICO score rose from 540 to 680 and the bank upgraded her to an unsecured card.',
      related: ['credit-utilization', 'credit-score', 'apr', 'minimum-payment'],
