      shortDef: 'The maximum rate at which your body can consume oxygen during intense exercise—the gold standard measure of cardiovascular fitness.',
      fullDef: 'VO2 max (maximal oxygen uptake) is the maximum volume of oxygen your body can use per minute during exhaustive exercise, expressed as mL/kg/min. It is the primary determinant of aerobic endurance performance and a strong predictor of cardiovascular health and all-cause mortality. Average VO2 max for untrained adults is roughly 35–40 for women and 42–46 for men; elite endurance athletes may reach 70–85+.\n\nVO2 max is determined by both central factors (cardiac output—how much blood the heart pumps) and peripheral factors (how efficiently muscles extract oxygen from blood). It can be improved through training—particularly high-intensity cardio intervals—typically by 10–25% from baseline for untrained individuals. After the initial gains, further improvement requires increasingly specific training.\n\nVO2 max declines approximately 10% per decade after age 25 without training. Regular aerobic exercise significantly slows this decline. Recent research from the Cooper Clinic identifies low VO2 max as a stronger mortality risk factor than smoking, hypertension, or diabetes—making cardiorespiratory fitness a major public health priority.',
