      fullDef: 'Metabolism encompasses all chemical reactions that sustain life, but in the fitness context it usually refers to the body\'s total calorie-burning capacity: TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure). TDEE has three components: Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)—calories burned at complete rest, comprising 60–70% of TDEE; the Thermic Effect of Food (TEF)—calories burned digesting food, ~10%; and Activity Energy Expenditure—calories from both planned exercise and non-exercise activity thermogenesis (NEAT), comprising 20–30%.\n\nMetabolism is often cited as a reason for weight gain ("slow metabolism") but metabolic variation between people of the same size is actually modest—roughly 200–300 calories per day. The more significant variable is NEAT: the calories burned from fidgeting, posture, walking, and incidental movement. NEAT varies enormously between individuals and decreases significantly during caloric restriction (metabolic adaptation).\n\nFactors that genuinely affect metabolism include: lean muscle mass (more muscle = higher BMR), thyroid function, age (BMR declines ~2% per decade after 20), hormonal status, and sleep quality. Resistance training increases lean muscle mass and is the most effective long-term strategy for sustaining a higher metabolic rate.',
