      letter: 'P',
      shortDef: 'A period during a diet or training program when progress stalls despite continued effort, usually requiring an adjustment to stimuli or caloric targets.',
      fullDef: 'A weight loss or fitness plateau occurs when progress halts despite maintaining the same behaviors that were previously producing results. In weight loss, plateaus typically occur because: (1) metabolic adaptation has reduced TDEE to match the new calorie intake, (2) calorie intake has unconsciously crept up, (3) activity has unconsciously decreased (NEAT suppression in response to caloric restriction), or (4) water retention masks ongoing fat loss.\n\nIn resistance training, a plateau occurs when the current training stimulus is no longer novel enough to drive adaptation—the muscles have fully adapted to the current weight, volume, and frequency. This is normal and expected; training programs should be periodized to introduce new stimuli before full adaptation occurs.\n\nFor weight loss plateaus, strategies include: recalculating TDEE (the body is smaller now), implementing a diet break (returning to maintenance calories for 1–2 weeks to reduce adaptive metabolic suppression), increasing activity (particularly NEAT), or confirming calorie tracking accuracy. True metabolic resistance is rare; most plateaus respond to honest assessment and adjustment.',
