      shortDef: 'The physiological process of repairing and adapting after exercise stress, requiring adequate sleep, nutrition, and rest days to prevent overtraining.',
      fullDef: 'Exercise adaptation—getting stronger, faster, fitter—does not happen during training; it happens during recovery. Training creates stimulus (micro-damage to muscle fibers, depletion of energy stores, hormonal signals); recovery is when the body repairs and rebuilds stronger than before. Insufficient recovery leads to underperformance, injury, and overtraining syndrome.\n\nKey recovery modalities include: sleep (7–9 hours for most adults—the single most impactful recovery tool, when GH secretion and muscle protein synthesis peak), nutrition (protein and carbohydrate intake around training facilitates repair), active recovery (low-intensity movement on rest days maintains blood flow and clears metabolic waste), and stress management (cortisol from life stress competes with recovery signals).\n\nOvertraining syndrome—caused by chronic training load exceeding recovery capacity—presents as persistent fatigue, declining performance, mood disturbances, elevated resting heart rate, and increased injury frequency. It requires weeks to months of reduced training to resolve. The rule for preventing it: progress should be driven by adding training stress gradually, not by eliminating recovery.',
