      fullDef: 'BMI (Body Mass Index) is calculated as weight (kg) / height (m²). The WHO categories are: Underweight (<18.5), Normal weight (18.5–24.9), Overweight (25–29.9), Obese Class I (30–34.9), Obese Class II (35–39.9), and Obese Class III (≥40). BMI was developed in the 19th century as a population statistics tool—it was never intended as an individual diagnostic measure.\n\nBMI\'s primary limitation is that it cannot distinguish between fat mass and lean mass. A muscular athlete with 8% body fat may have a BMI of 28 (overweight) while a sedentary person with 32% body fat may have a BMI of 24 (normal). It also has racial bias—Asian populations carry greater metabolic risk at lower BMI thresholds; the WHO recommends lower cutoffs for Asian populations.\n\nDespite its limitations, BMI remains widely used because it requires only height and weight, is free, and correlates reasonably well with health outcomes at the population level. Better individual measures of adiposity—waist circumference, waist-to-height ratio, DEXA body composition scan—provide more clinically useful information but require more resources.',
