      fullDef: 'Resistance training (also called strength training or weight training) involves exercising muscles against an external resistance to create mechanical tension and metabolic stress that drives adaptation. Methods include: free weights (barbells, dumbbells), machines, resistance bands, bodyweight exercises, and cable systems. The adaptive responses include increased muscle fiber size (hypertrophy), neural adaptations (better motor unit recruitment), increased bone density, and improved metabolic health markers.\n\nBeyond aesthetics, resistance training has profound health benefits: it is the primary driver of metabolic rate maintenance during aging, reduces all-cause mortality, improves insulin sensitivity, reduces fracture risk through bone density increases, and is among the most effective interventions for depression and anxiety. Physical Activity Guidelines for Americans recommend at least two sessions per week for all adults.\n\nFor fat loss, resistance training is important for preserving muscle mass during a caloric deficit. Without it, a significant portion of weight lost in a caloric deficit comes from muscle—reducing metabolic rate and producing a soft rather than lean physique. The combination of moderate caloric deficit plus progressive resistance training produces the best body composition outcomes.',
