      fullDef: 'Intermittent fasting (IF) is not a specific diet but an eating schedule that restricts the timing of food consumption. The most popular protocols are 16:8 (16 hours fasting, 8-hour eating window daily), 5:2 (eating normally 5 days per week, restricting to 500–600 calories 2 non-consecutive days), and alternate-day fasting. Some people also use extended fasts of 24–48 hours occasionally.\n\nResearch shows IF produces fat loss comparable to continuous caloric restriction when total calorie intake is equated—its primary mechanism is helping people eat fewer calories by limiting the opportunity to eat. Additional proposed benefits include improved insulin sensitivity, reduced inflammatory markers, and cellular autophagy (cleanup of damaged cellular components), though long-term human data on these mechanisms is still developing.\n\nIF is not appropriate for everyone: people with a history of eating disorders, pregnant or breastfeeding women, those with certain medical conditions, and people who become hypoglycemic when fasting should consult a physician before attempting IF. The best eating pattern for weight loss is the one you can maintain consistently—IF works well for some people and poorly for others.',
