      fullDef: 'NEAT encompasses all physical activity outside of formal exercise: walking, standing, fidgeting, climbing stairs, household tasks, and even posture maintenance. Research by Dr. James Levine at the Mayo Clinic found that NEAT can vary by up to 2,000 calories per day between individuals of similar size—far more than the variation accounted for by formal exercise or metabolism.\n\nNEAT is highly sensitive to caloric intake. When calories are restricted, the body unconsciously reduces NEAT (people fidget less, sit more, move less efficiently) as a compensatory energy-sparing mechanism. This is a major contributor to weight loss plateaus and explains why formal exercise does not always produce the expected caloric deficit—the exercise calories are partially offset by NEAT reduction.\n\nIncreasing NEAT—taking the stairs, parking farther, standing desk, walking meetings, pacing while on calls—can add 200–500 calories of expenditure per day for most people. Step count (10,000 steps/day = approximately 400–500 calories) is a practical proxy for NEAT. Unlike formal exercise, NEAT can be increased throughout every waking hour.',
