      fullDef: 'Muscle protein synthesis (MPS) is the process by which the body builds new contractile proteins (actin and myosin) in muscle fibers in response to training stimuli and amino acid availability. It is the fundamental mechanism of muscle growth (hypertrophy) and repair. MPS is stimulated by resistance exercise and by adequate protein intake, particularly the essential amino acid leucine.\n\nMPS is elevated for approximately 24–48 hours after a resistance training session. Protein intake distributed across 3–4 meals per day (each containing 30–40g of high-quality protein) maximizes the MPS stimulus throughout the day. A single large protein meal is less effective than distributed intake because there is a ceiling on how much MPS a single dose can stimulate.\n\nEssential amino acid content—and particularly leucine—determines a protein source\'s anabolic potency. Whey protein (a fast-digesting dairy protein high in leucine) is particularly effective at stimulating MPS. Complete protein sources (meat, fish, eggs, dairy, and certain plant combinations) provide all essential amino acids necessary for MPS.',
