      fullDef: 'Compound exercises involve multiple joints and recruit multiple muscle groups in a single movement. Examples include squats (quad, glute, hamstring, core), deadlifts (hamstring, glute, back, core), bench press (chest, shoulder, tricep), and pull-ups (back, bicep, core). They produce greater hormonal response, burn more calories per set, build more functional strength, and allow heavier loading than isolation exercises.\n\nIsolation exercises (also called single-joint exercises) target one muscle group with one joint movement: bicep curls, leg extensions, lateral raises, tricep pushdowns. They are used to address weak points, provide additional volume to lagging muscles, and provide targeted hypertrophy stimulus when compound movements cannot provide sufficient direct work.\n\nOptimal programs typically prioritize compound movements for the core of each session (they produce the greatest systemic training stimulus) and use isolation exercises as supplementary work for specific development goals. Beginners benefit most from compound movements; advanced lifters often need more isolation work to continue developing specific muscle groups.',
