      shortDef: 'A planned period of reduced training volume or intensity to allow accumulated fatigue to dissipate and prepare the body for the next hard training block.',
      fullDef: 'A deload is a strategic reduction in training load—typically a week of reduced volume (fewer sets), reduced intensity (lighter weights), or both—built into training programs at regular intervals. Its purpose is to dissipate accumulated fatigue (both physical and neurological) that builds over weeks of progressive training, allowing full recovery and often producing performance improvements in the subsequent training block.\n\nDeloads are distinct from forced rest due to injury. They are proactive, planned reductions that experienced athletes use to maximize long-term progress. The training science principle is supercompensation: after a period of training-induced fatigue, reducing the stress allows the body to not just recover to baseline but to temporarily exceed it—if the timing and magnitude of the deload are correct.\n\nA common implementation is a deload every 4–8 weeks of progressive training, reducing volume by 30–50% while maintaining or slightly reducing intensity. Frequency stays the same. Signs that a deload is needed include: persistent soreness, declining performance, poor sleep, mood changes, and loss of motivation.',
