      fullDef: 'Hydration is the maintenance of adequate body water balance. The body is approximately 60% water; even mild dehydration (1–2% of body weight) measurably reduces aerobic performance, strength output, and cognitive function. For a 150-pound athlete, that is just 1.5–3 pounds of water loss—achievable in a single moderately intense workout without fluid replacement.\n\nHydration needs vary based on body size, sweat rate, temperature, humidity, and exercise intensity. General recommendations (8 glasses/day) are oversimplified; urine color is a more practical guide—pale yellow indicates adequate hydration. For athletes, weighing before and after training and replacing each pound of weight lost with 16–20 oz of fluid is a precise approach to post-exercise rehydration.\n\nDuring prolonged exercise (>60 minutes), plain water alone is insufficient—electrolyte replacement (sodium in particular) is needed to prevent hyponatremia (dangerously low sodium levels from drinking too much plain water) and to optimize fluid retention. Sports drinks, electrolyte tablets, or salted foods provide the sodium that makes fluid replacement effective.',
