      shortDef: 'Adequate sleep (7–9 hours) supports weight loss by regulating hunger hormones, reducing cravings, and enabling muscle recovery; sleep deprivation sabotages fat loss.',
      fullDef: 'Sleep is a profoundly underappreciated variable in body composition management. Sleep deprivation (less than 6 hours per night) increases ghrelin (the hunger hormone) and decreases leptin (the satiety hormone), producing increased appetite—on average 300–400 extra calories per day in sleep-deprived versus well-rested individuals. It also increases cravings specifically for high-calorie, high-carbohydrate foods through effects on the endocannabinoid system.\n\nA landmark study found that during caloric restriction with adequate sleep, 55% of weight lost came from fat; with sleep deprivation, only 25% came from fat—the rest came from lean mass. Sleep-deprived dieters lost the same total weight but lost significantly more muscle and less fat. This makes adequate sleep non-negotiable for anyone prioritizing body composition over pure weight loss.\n\nAdditionally, sleep is when growth hormone is primarily secreted (driving muscle repair and fat mobilization) and when the brain consolidates motor patterns from training. Seven to nine hours of quality sleep is as important as diet and training for body composition—not a soft lifestyle factor but a hard performance requirement.',
